          "chapter_id": "ac85c45b-4e73-4b15-9914-106bf4d48862",
          "chunk_index": null,
          "content": "Each barefoot step on the cold, unforgiving stone was a profound, private wager, where the slightest misstep risked the betrayal of a clank, a dry scrape, or any clatter that might announce his small, forbidden errand. This was no mere silence; it was a coiled, ancient emptiness that smelled of sulfur and expectant soil—the still patience of serpents in a garden. This was no home, but the heavy, unmoving lair of a man devoted to the earth's sheer, magnetic pull. Therefore, the boy's every calculated movement toward his father’s room was an act of quiet, necessary heresy.",
